All Implemented Interfaces:
TimingTarget
@Immutable(implementationOnly=true)
public abstract class KeyFramesTimingTarget<T>
extends TimingTargetAdapter

Abstract timing target that allows interpolation of values throughout an animation via key frames.

If your animation simply changes a property on an object then consider using the PropertySetter utility instead of extending this class.

Author:
Tim Halloran

timingEvent

public void timingEvent(Animator source,
                        double fraction)
Description copied from interface: TimingTarget
This method will receive all of the timing events during an animation. The fraction is the percent elapsed (0 to 1) of the current animation cycle.

Specified by:
timingEvent in interface TimingTarget
Overrides:
timingEvent in class TimingTargetAdapter
Parameters:
source - the animation.
fraction - the fraction of completion between the start and end of the current cycle. Note that on reversing cycles ( Animator.Direction.BACKWARD) the fraction decreases from 1.0 to 0 on backwards-running cycles. Note also that animations with a duration of INFINITE will have an undefined value for the fraction, since there is no fraction that makes sense if the animation has no defined length.

valueAtTimingEvent

public abstract void valueAtTimingEvent(T value,
                                        double fraction,
                                        Animator source)
This method will receive the interpolated value at each timing event during an animation. It is directly invoked by the timingEvent(Animator, double) method in the following manner: 
 public void timingEvent(Animator source, double fraction) {
   valueAtTimingEvent(getKeyFrames().getInterpolatedValueAt(fraction), fraction, source);
 }
If timingEvent(Animator, double) is overridden by the implementation and the above snippet does not appear then this method will not be invoked.

The fraction is the percent elapsed (0 to 1) of the current animation cycle.

Parameters:
value - the interpolated value, determined using the object's key frames.
source - the animation.
fraction - the fraction of completion between the start and end of the current cycle. Note that on reversing cycles ( Animator.Direction.BACKWARD) the fraction decreases from 1.0 to 0 on backwards-running cycles. Note also that animations with a duration of INFINITE will have an undefined value for the fraction, since there is no fraction that makes sense if the animation has no defined length.
